  <li>WestJet</li></ul>In its AirTag 2 press release, Apple said it has partnered with more than 50 airlines, so there should be around 15 more that support the feature soon.<br/>
<br/>
<h2>How to Use the Feature</h2><br/>
iPhone, iPad, and Mac users can generate a "Share Item Location" link in the Find My app. Anyone they share the link with can then view a web page with a location of the item on a map. The page will automatically update with the item's latest known location.<br/>
<br/>
<img src="https://images.macrumors.com/article-new/2024/11/iOS-18-2-Share-Item-Location.jpg" alt="" width="1600" height="900" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-976718" /><br/>
The item's location stops being shared "as soon as a user is reunited with their item," or automatically expires after seven days.<br/>
<br/>
On the iPhone, the feature was introduced on iOS 18.2, but Apple says the AirTag 2 requires an iPhone running iOS 26.2.1 or later. If you are still running iOS 18.2 through iOS 18.7.4, you will need to use the original AirTag or a supported third-party tracker.<br/>
<br/>
